header.title: Meditations on The Cube of Space

central_thesis: The Cube of Space serves as a profound cosmological model for practical spiritual work, enabling the practitioner to understand and interact with divine forces, expand consciousness, and achieve self-transformation. Through structured meditations involving Hebrew letters, Tarot keys, planetary/zodiacal attributions, sound, and color, individuals can access and integrate inner spiritual wealth, leading to the 'Grip of the Soul' and conscious direction of their personal reality.

structure_content.summary: This chapter establishes the book's purpose as a practical manual complementing the theoretical 'The Cube of Space' (Volume One). It outlines a system of meditations using the Cube's structure and its connections to hermetic sciences, aiming for personal transformation. The author emphasizes the deep occult application of Tarot, integrating symbols from alchemy, astrology, and Qabalah, and warns that the practices are designed to induce spiritual growth, which may involve 'spiritual crises'.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter I: Limitation, The Power of Creation
structure_content.summary: This chapter introduces the Cube as a fundamental container, symbolizing limitation (Cheth, Saturn) as a necessary creative force that defines and structures chaotic potential ('radiant darkness' or Ayin). Meditations begin at the Cube's central point, focusing on Divine Names, Key 21 (The World), and the Tattvic symbol of Akasha-Akasha, to establish a conscious center of expression.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter II: Sealing and Binding the Cube of Space
structure_content.summary: This chapter details the process of creating space through the 'sealing' of the six directions using the three Hebrew Mother letters (Aleph, Mem, Shin) and permutations of YHVH. Meditations involve visualizing these directions with corresponding Tarot keys, planets, sounds, and colors, thereby establishing the initial boundaries and structure of the Cube of Space.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter III: Self-Conscious and Subconscious Aspects of the Cardinal Points
structure_content.summary: This chapter explores the interplay between self-conscious and subconscious levels of awareness, linked by four cardinal planetary Tarot keys (Empress, Tower, Wheel of Fortune, Sun). Meditations focus on connecting these keys and their associated zodiacal signs to the 'Above' and 'Below' faces of the Cube, aiming to harmonize the spiritual impulses descending and ascending through these states of consciousness.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter IV: The Law of Polarity
structure_content.summary: This chapter delves into the universal Law of Polarity, demonstrating its manifestation through the three Mother letters and the cardinal directions. It describes how each Mother letter acts as a reconciler of opposing forces. Meditations involve polar opposite Tarot keys (e.g., Magician/High Priestess, Empress/Wheel of Fortune, Sun/Tower) to integrate extremes and achieve balance within the practitioner's being.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter V: Zodiacal Polarity The Above and The Below
structure_content.summary: Expanding on polarity, this chapter examines zodiacal polarities as they manifest on the 'Above' and 'Below' lines of the Cube's East, West, North, and South faces. Meditations utilize specific zodiacal keys and their ruling planets (e.g., Gemini/Sagittarius for East Above/West Below) to gain a deeper understanding of these complex interactions and the flow of creative forces.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter VI: Polarity and the Zodiacal Year
structure_content.summary: This chapter systematizes the six pairs of zodiacal opposites based on their positions within the year (equinoxes, solstices, cross-quarters) and introduces 'Alchemical Sky' relationships. Meditations focus on these zodiacal pairs (e.g., Aries/Libra, Cancer/Capricorn) to balance elemental energies, using corresponding Tarot keys, sounds, and colors to align the practitioner with cosmic cycles of light and darkness.

This chapter introduces the five Hebrew 'final letters' (Kaph final, Mem final, Nun final, Peh final, Tzaddi final) as symbolic diagonals within the Cube of Space. These diagonals represent pathways for the initiate to access the Cube's center and integrate subconscious and superconscious intelligences into self-conscious awareness, facilitating a deeper understanding of manifestation and linking different Tree of Life spheres.

This chapter focuses on the Hebrew letter Mem (D), which holds a unique position as a Mother letter, a Final letter, and dwelling at the center of the Cube, symbolizing 'Wholeness, Perfection, and Completeness' (Mem-Nun). Meditations utilize Tarot Keys 12 (Hanged Man) and 21 (The World) to connect with this central intelligence and channel its influence to the Cube's exterior faces, emphasizing the Buddhic plane and intuitive awareness.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter IX: The Planetary Orders and the Attributions to the Minor Trumps
structure_content.summary: This chapter provides a theoretical foundation for understanding the Minor Arcana. It outlines various systems of planetary attributions (Elemental Triplicities, Esoteric, Hierarchy, Chaldean) for the decanates of the zodiac. The core method for practical work is presented: articulating a minor key by identifying and meditating on its constituent Major Arcana keys, which represent the associated sphere, sign, and planetary rulers (using Elemental Triplicities).

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter X: Meditations on the Minor Arcana
structure_content.summary: This chapter initiates the practical meditations on the Minor Arcana, starting with the decanates of Aries (Two, Three, and Four of Wands). Each meditation systematically links a minor key to a specific Tree of Life sphere, zodiacal sign, planetary rulers, sound, and color. The goal is to gain a deeper understanding of the inherent symbolism and facilitate self-transformation through focused attention on these complex attributions. Key words are provided for personality-level interpretation.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter XI: The Three Decanates of 8
structure_content.summary: Continuing the Minor Arcana meditations, this chapter focuses on the decanates of Taurus (Five, Six, and Seven of Pentacles). It explores Taurus as a fixed earthy sign representing the descent of spiritual principles into physical manifestation and the development of 'volition' (the will expressed through personality). Meditations aim to cultivate positive aspects of will, foster solar consciousness, and guide the manifestation of creative images into tangible forms.

structure_content.chapter_title: Chapter XII: The Decanates of II
structure_content.summary: This chapter covers meditations on the decanates of Gemini (Eight, Nine, and Ten of Swords). Gemini is presented as a mutable air sign associated with 'fixation'â€”the establishment of boundaries and containers for the three alchemical principles (Salt, Sulfur, Mercury). Meditations focus on refining mental patterns, transforming erroneous thought forms, and allowing the soul to express its Buddhic nature, thus leading to clarity and discrimination.

The Seven of Pentacles represents the manifestation of the planet Venus in the world of expression, particularly connected to the development of will and desire. It symbolizes a twofold transition from the lower Egoic Triad to the higher, urging purification of desires to align with the One Will. The card's location on the southeast ascending line signifies ascent from subconscious to self-conscious awareness, emphasizing the process of transforming creative images into tangible physical forms, guided by intuition from the Inner Teacher. Its key meaning is LOSS, encouraging detachment from outcomes while focusing on the purity of intention.

key_concepts.definition: A cosmological model representing the structure of manifestation, used as a framework for meditation and understanding hermetic sciences. It serves as a container for divine forces and human consciousness, generated geometrically and composed of twenty-seven cubic units.

The fundamental creative force (represented by the Hebrew letter Cheth and the planet Saturn) that defines boundaries and enables specific manifestation from the undifferentiated sea of chaotic potential. It is the root of form and order.
The boundless, limitless light and chaotic potential of the universe from which all forms emerge. It is the 'No-Thing' that is contained and specified through limitation.

Three primary Hebrew letters representing fundamental elements (Air, Water, Fire) that establish axes and create the six directions in space. They act as reconciling forces between polarities, originating from the center of the Cube and extending to its faces.

Vibratory formulae (e.g., Eheyah, Jehovah, Elohim, Adonai, YHVH, YHVH-Elohim-Va-Daath, YHVH-Tzabaoth, Shaddai El Chai, Adonai Ha Eretz) attributed to spheres on the Tree of Life or specific intelligences. These names are chanted during meditations to attune to and evoke archetypal energies and forces.

Specific Major and Minor Arcana cards used as focal points in meditations. Each key corresponds to spheres on the Tree of Life, planets, zodiacal signs, and elemental attributions, serving as a symbolic medium to plant suggestions within the subconscious mind.

A symbol representing the intelligence at the center of the Cube, depicted by two concentric vesicae. It embodies the qualities of space and sound, attributed to Key 21 (The World) and the planet Saturn, indicating the point of focus and origin of manifestation.

A universal Hermetic principle stating that 'everything is dual; everything has poles; everything has its pair of opposites; like and unlike are the same; opposites are identical in nature, but different in degree; extremes meet; all truths are but half-truths; all paradoxes may be reconciled.' This law is applied to the Cube's axes, directions, and zodiacal pairs to understand the interplay of forces.

Five Hebrew letters (Kaph final, Mem final, Nun final, Peh final, Tzaddi final) that take on a special form at the end of a word. In the Cube of Space, they represent 'diagonals' that facilitate the flow of intelligence from the 'below' corners, through the center, to the diametrically opposite 'above' corners, distributing subconscious and superconscious awareness.

Ten-degree arcs within each zodiacal sign, totaling 36 decanates in the zodiacal wheel. Each decanate is ruled by a specific planet (according to elemental triplicities) and corresponds to a Minor Arcana key, providing a granular system for understanding planetary and zodiacal influences.

Processes attributed to zodiacal signs (e.g., Calcination, Congelation, Fixation, Separation, Digestion, Distillation, Sublimation, Putrefaction, Incineration, Fermentation, Dissolution, Multiplication). These represent stages of spiritual and psychological transformation within the personality, allowing for the breakdown, purification, and recombination of energies.

The central self or soul, represented by the sixth sphere on the Tree of Life. The conscious direction of the personality by the Divine Ego is the ultimate goal of the 'Great Work' and the process of transmutation, moving beyond the 'struggling separated personality'.

An angelic force representing higher consciousness (Key 14, Temperance) that guides purification and transformation. It is released upon the 'destruction of the causal body' and assists in incinerating erroneous thought forms, leading to true wisdom.

The universal, unformed substance or 'magical earth' that is receptive to creative images and thought forms. It is the underlying material upon which the creator imprints intentions for manifestation, particularly associated with the subconscious mind.

practical_system.description: The system presented is a series of structured meditations using the Cube of Space as a multi-dimensional glyph. It integrates Hebrew letters, Tarot Major and Minor Arcana, planetary and zodiacal attributions, and specific sound/color correspondences. The practice follows a sequential order, beginning with the Cube's central point and progressively moving through its six directions, six faces, four diagonals, and the thirty-six decanates of the zodiac. The overall goal is to expand consciousness, harmonize internal polarities, facilitate contact with higher intelligences, and enable conscious self-transformation by reshaping mental patterns and aligning individual will with divine will.
tools: Tarot Deck (preferably Paul Foster Case's B.O.T.A. deck, with specific Major and Minor Arcana keys)
Knowledge of Hebrew letters and their Qabalistic attributions (numerical values, meanings, elemental associations)
Knowledge of Astrological symbols (planets, zodiacal signs, decanate rulers) and their occult correspondences
Knowledge of Alchemical principles and their attributed operations
A portable keyboard (optional, for precise musical note intonation)
Concentrated visualization skills for colors, symbols, and internal flows of energy
Ability to chant/intonate specific musical notes and Divine/Angelic Names
rituals: Daily Attunement with four Divine Names (Eheyah, Jehovah, Elohim, Adonai) for high-level consciousness.
Central Point Meditation focusing on Key 21 (The World) and Akasha-Akasha symbol, chanting 'ah-oo-um' (note A) and visualizing blue-violet light.
'Hear Oh Israel' Meditation using Tarot Keys 0, 12, and 20 (Aleph, Mem, Shin) and intoning 'She-Ma-Ah' to create energetic axes.

Sealing the Six Directions: Visualizing each direction (Above, Below, East, West, North, South) with specific permutations of YHVH, corresponding Tarot keys, colors, and musical notes (e.g., Key 1, Yellow, E for 'Above').
Binding the Faces with Zodiacal Permutations of YHVH: Meditating on twelve permutations of YHVH associated with zodiacal signs (e.g., Aries, Taurus, Gemini) to define the Cube's faces.
Self-Conscious and Subconscious Aspect Meditations: Focusing on cardinal planetary Tarot keys (Empress, Tower, Wheel of Fortune, Sun) and their links to the Above and Below faces.

Law of Polarity Meditations: Working with pairs of polar opposite Tarot keys and their attributions (e.g., Magician/High Priestess for Above/Below, Empress/Wheel of Fortune for East/West) to reconcile dualities.

The Four Diagonals Meditations: Tracing the paths of Hebrew 'final letters' (Kaph final, Mem final, Nun final, Peh final, Tzaddi final) through the Cube, using sequences of Tarot keys and specific chants to distribute central intelligence.

Minor Arcana Decanate Meditations: Articulating each minor key (e.g., Two of Wands for Aries) by laying out its corresponding Major Arcana keys (representing sphere, sign, planet/sub-ruler), chanting divine/angelic names, notes, and visualizing colors to understand its specific influence and alchemical operation. Each meditation concludes with a specific 'key word' (e.g., Dominion, Uncertainty, Mediocrity, Destruction, Loss, Harvest, Instability, Swiftness, Management, Defeat, Instability, Excess).
Mothers of Fire and Water / Air and Water: Specific meditations combining Key 12 (Hanged Man) and Key 20 (Judgement) or Key 0 (The Fool) and Key 12 (Hanged Man) to understand elemental interactions.

relevant_quotes.text: This book is respectfully dedicated to all the ministers of Love and Good Will around the world; to my mother, Dolores, who was my first teacher and example of how to love, and to the Coming One whose nature is Love.

If divination is your only goal concerning the Tarot, this work is not for you. There are hundreds of great books on the subject on reading Tarot cards and this is not one of them. This is a book on the occult application of the Tarot in conjunction with the Cube of Space.
Knowledge of the Tarot, and how to use it properly will allow the student to speak eloquently on all subjects.
This work is designed to create a series of spiritual crises in the lives of those who take on this work. Comfort in not the goal although the reader should be mindful not to overdo it.

Our continual expansion of our individual containers ultimately results in the very destruction of the form that has been our womb. As in all birthing processes, the womb acts as a temporary container, which will eventually expel the child who has lived therein.

Everything is dual; everything has poles; everything has its pair of opposites; like and unlike are the same; opposites are identical in nature, but different in degree; extremes meet; all truths are but half-truths; all paradoxes may be reconciled.
In the beginning the creative powers of the Life Breath separated the Heavens from the Earth.
Gjender is in everything; everything has its masculine and feminine principle; Cjender manifest on all planes.
I am the sword, The sword which is understanding, Dividing between the darkness and the light At creations dawn.
My secret wisdom is hid in number, And in the sign of the Tally Is concealed the building of the whole of creation.
I am the creative Hand, Which fashioneth the worlds And establisheth the spheres, While yet the primal FIRE Circleth untrammeled in the womb of space.
Incineration burns to ashes the dross and refuse of the old ways of thinking. It consumes all the residue of our erroneous interpretations of experience.

The aspirant who builds his Dweller and permits its steady and increasing control becomes a deluder of souls. He is a true Anti-Christ, and through false teaching and the working of so-called miracles, through hypnotism and mass suggestion he draws a veil over the world and forces men to walk in the great illusion. It is interesting to note that the work of the Devil, the imprisoner of souls is beginning to lose its power, for the race is on the verge of understanding true death is immersion in form, and matter is but a part of the divine whole.
The twenty-third path is called the stable intelligence. It is so called because it is the source of consistency among all the Sephiroth.

critical_analysis.relevance: This book provides a rigorous, practical system for applying Qabalistic and Hermetic principles through the cosmological model of the Cube of Space. It bridges abstract theory with operative magical practice, demonstrating how integrated elements like Tarot, Hebrew letters, astrology, and alchemy can be used for deep self-transformation. Its relevance lies in offering advanced students a structured path to experiential contact with spiritual forces, expanding consciousness, and consciously shaping their reality. It explicitly distinguishes itself from casual Tarot reading, focusing on a profound occult application.
critical_analysis.target_audience: The primary target audience is advanced students of Western Esotericism, Qabalah, Hermeticism, and Tarot who possess a foundational understanding of 'The Cube of Space' (Volume One) and its underlying cosmology. It is not suitable for beginners or those seeking simple divination, as the language, concepts, and practices demand significant prior knowledge and a commitment to sustained, often challenging, spiritual work leading to 'spiritual crises' and profound personal growth.
